## Incident investigation lifecycle

### Step 1: Confirm it's an incident

Validate against the incident definition:

> An unplanned event impacting users or increasing risk to production.

If **not** an incident:

- Route to normal support (create an issue or ticket)
- If security-related, follow Cyber Security reporting procedures

---

### Step 2: Declare and set visibility

#### PagerDuty Status Page

- Select impacted service(s)
  - AP Ingestion
  - AP Storage
  - AP Compute
  - AP Networking
  - AP Identity
- Choose impact:
  - Major
  - Minor
  - All Good
- Set **Time till Next Update**
- Tick **Send update notifications**
- Publish

This will notify subscribers and automatically post into Slack support channels.

#### Slack

- Post an initial summary in the incident thread (see template below)
- Pin the Incident Report link

---

### Step 3: Establish roles and assemble team

- Confirm IL and CL in the thread header
- Identify SMRs and owners for affected components
- For P1/P2 incidents:
  - Notify PM and DM immediately
  - Agree communication cadence

---

### Step 4: Classify & Plan

- Set priority (P1–P4) with rationale
- Record priority in the Incident Report
- Define:
  - First investigative steps
  - Success criteria
- Decide whether to:
  - Roll back
  - Feature flag
  - Change configuration
  - Isolate affected components

---

### Step 5: Investigate (evidence-driven)

Gather evidence:

- Logs
- Metrics
- Traces
- Dashboards
- Recent deployments
- Dependency health

Work iteratively:

- Form hypotheses
- Test hypotheses
- Record:
  - Every action
  - Commands executed
  - Results

If a third-party issue is suspected:

- Raise vendor support tickets
- Include:
  - Correlation IDs
  - Timestamps

#### AWS Support

- Log a support case in the affected AWS account
- Follow:
  - *Creating a support case*
- Escalate:
  - On the AWS case
  - Or via `#ext-aws`

---

### Step 6: Contain (Security/Data Incidents)

- Short‑term: isolate affected systems, rotate credentials, disable compromised accounts/keys; minimise user impact.
- Forensics: preserve evidence; document all commands.
- Long‑term: reimage or restore from known‑good backups; harden affected systems.


---

### Step 7: Use mitigations or workarounds

- Implement safe workarounds (e.g., scale capacity, failover, feature toggle, rate limiting).
- Communicate user‑visible impacts and timelines via Status Page and Slack.

---

### Step 8: Remove root cause and related artefacts

- Identify all affected hosts/services; remove malware/artefacts; patch/reimage as needed.
- Verify backups, code, images, and systems are protected against recurrence.

---

### Step 9: Recover

- Decide when to restore to production; verify environment is not compromised in the same way.
- Define post‑restore monitoring window.
- Reduce incident priority when appropriate and update comms accordingly.

---

### Step 10: Communicate

- Maintain updates per priority table; include impact, actions taken, next update time.
- Internal: Slack thread updates; External: Status Page notifications to subscribers.
- Manage escalations (e.g., to programme leadership, Cyber Security, vendors).

---

### Step 11: End the incident

- Confirm users are no longer facing issues (even if a temporary fix is in place).
- Update Status Page to All Good with resolution summary and any follow-up work.
- Announce closure in Slack thread; set final status in Incident Report

---

### Step 12: Learn and follow up

- Create/complete Incident Report (timeline, decisions, evidence, impact, root cause, lessons).
- Hold a blameless post‑mortem; identify actions to prevent recurrence or improve detection.
- Publish/update runbooks; raise follow‑up tickets with owners & due dates; update the AP incident log.

